26 SECTION 39. IC 15-16-2-49.7 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
27 CODE A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
28 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 49.7. For purposes of imposing civil penalties
29 under this chapter, the state chemist shall comply with the
30 following when determining the violation number and the count of
31 violations:
32 (1) Only violations committed within the immediate past five
33 (5) years of the date of the violation being addressed will be
34 considered.
35 (2) A person's violation numbers shall accumulate as first,
36 second, third, and so on independently for each violation
37 listed on the schedule.
38 (3) When multiple different but similar or related violations
39 are committed by a single distinguishable act or failure to act,
40 only one (1) of those violations may be subject to a civil
41 penalty for that act. This subdivision is intended to avoid
42 duplicating civil penalty assessment for violation of multiple
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

31
1 provisions of the statute or rule that may be essentially the
2 same or closely related. This subdivision is not intended to
3 limit in any way civil penalty assessment for violations that
4 are the result of more than one (1) distinguishable unrelated
5 act or failure to act or a violation of a continuing or repetitive
6 nature.
7 (4) When civil penalty assessment procedures outlined in
8 subdivision (3) are being followed, the state chemist shall use
9 the appropriate violation with the highest penalty listed on the
10 schedule.
11 SECTION 40. IC 15-16-2-49.8 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
12 CODE A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
13 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 49.8. (a) Except as provided in section 49.6 of
14 this chapter, the amount of a civil penalty in section 49.6 of this
15 chapter may be adjusted downward to reflect particular mitigating
16 factors. Some factors that may be considered are the following:
17 (1) Good faith efforts of the violator to comply.
18 (2) Cooperation by the violator with the state chemist during
19 the investigation process.
20 (3) The violator's history of compliance.
21 (4) The potential for damage.
22 (5) Remedial or corrective action taken by the violator.
23 (b) The state chemist may subject the violator to the full amount
24 of the nonmitigated civil penalty if the violator fails to pay the full
25 amount of any previously mitigated civil penalty by the date
26 prescribed by the state chemist.
27 SECTION 41. IC 15-16-2-50, AS AMENDED BY P.L.81-2009,
28 SECTION 32, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
29 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 50. (a) Except as provided in subsection (b), a
30 political subdivision (as defined in IC 36-1-2-13) does not have
31 authority to regulate by ordinance the storage or use of fertilizer
32 material.
33 (b) A political subdivision may, by resolution, petition the state
34 chemist for a hearing to allow a waiver to adopt an ordinance because
35 of special circumstances relating to the storage or use of fertilizer
36 material. If a petition is received, the state chemist shall hold a public
37 hearing to consider allowing the waiver requested. The public hearing
38 must be conducted in an informal manner. IC 4-21.5 does not apply to
39 a public hearing under this section.
40 (c) The petitioner in the public hearing must present evidence
41 that supports the request for a waiver to adopt an ordinance. All
42 evidence shall be received fourteen (14) days prior to the hearing
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

32
1 date. The petitioner has the burden of showing the need for the
2 requested waiver. The evidence must include the following:
3 (1) A clear, detailed statement of the problem being
4 addressed.
5 (2) The special circumstances that exist that warrant a waiver.
6 (3) The specific political entity that will be covered by the
7 request.
8 (4) Any resources of the state that would be protected by the
9 request, including a specific stream, river, lake, or pond.
10 (5) Current site specific scientific data, including applicable
11 soil and water tests, that support the request.
12 (6) Previous mitigation methods or steps implemented.
13 (7) Educational efforts undertaken to address the concern.
14 (8) A copy of the proposed ordinance.
15 (d) In reaching a decision to approve or deny the waiver, the
16 state chemist shall consider the following:
17 (1) Whether the scientific evidence supports the claims being
18 made in the petition.
19 (2) Whether the measures proposed in the petition will likely
20 correct the purported problem or significantly reduce
21 environmental impacts.
22 (3) Whether the proposed ordinance corrects the problem in
23 the narrowest scope possible.
24 (4) Whether the ordinance will impose an undue burden upon
25 the persons regulated.
26 (5) Whether scientifically based maintenance levels of
27 nutrient applications would still be allowed by the ordinance.
28 (6) Acceptable fertilizer management practices.
29 (e) The state chemist may not consider the following factors in
30 making a decision on whether to approve or deny the waiver:
31 (1) The economic impact.
32 (2) The odor.
33 (f) In reaching a decision on whether to approve or deny the
34 waiver, the state chemist may consult, in addition to the material
35 received from the petitioner, the following:
36 (1) The board.
37 (2) Scientifically based materials provided by the College of
38 Agriculture at Purdue University.
39 (3) Other sources deemed necessary by the state chemist.
40 The state chemist shall prepare a written decision, with stated
41 reasons, either allowing or denying the waiver within ninety (90)
42 days after review.
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

