1 SECTION 42. IC 15-16-2.5 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
2 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
3 JULY 1, 2026]:
4 Chapter 2.5. Distributors and Users of Fertilizer Material
5 Sec. 1. (a) Except as provided in subsection (b), this chapter
6 applies to any person that:
7 (1) uses fertilizer material for hire on the property of another
8 person for purposes of producing an agricultural crop;
9 (2) uses organic fertilizer from a confined feeding operation
10 for purposes of producing an agricultural crop; or
11 (3) distributes fertilizer material directly to any person
12 described in this subsection.
13 (b) This chapter does not apply to any person that:
14 (1) uses or distributes less than ten (10) cubic yards or four
15 thousand (4,000) gallons of organic fertilizer obtained from a
16 confined feeding operation in a calendar year;
17 (2) uses biosolids, industrial waste products, and
18 pollutant-bearing water on land in Indiana that comply with
19 327 IAC 6.1; or
20 (3) distributes inorganic fertilizer to retail facilities.
21 Sec. 2. Fertilizer material used for hire on the property of
22 another person for purposes of producing an agricultural crop
23 must be used by:
24 (1) an individual who has a valid commercial applicator
25 license; or
26 (2) an individual who:
27 (A) is a trained employee; and
28 (B) is operating under the supervision of a certified
29 applicator.
30 Sec. 3. Organic fertilizer from a confined feeding operation used
31 for purposes of producing an agricultural crop must be used by:
32 (1) an individual who has a valid:
33 (A) commercial applicator license; or
34 (B) private applicator certification; or
35 (2) an individual who:
36 (A) is a trained employee; and
37 (B) is operating under the supervision of a certified
38 applicator.
39 Sec. 4. Fertilizer material distributed for the purpose of
40 producing an agricultural crop must be distributed:
41 (1) by a person that has a valid fertilizer business license; and
42 (2) to a person that has a valid:
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

34
1 (A) fertilizer business license;
2 (B) commercial applicator license; or
3 (C) private applicator certification.
4 Sec. 5. (a) Fertilizer materials covered by IC 15-16-2 and this
5 chapter may be used by a noncertified trained employee who is
6 working under the supervision of a certified applicator affiliated
7 with the person performing the use or distribution.
8 (b) The training required in this section must be:
9 (1) identified and approved by the state chemist; and
10 (2) repeated by the noncertified trained employee when that
11 individual moves from one employer to a different employer.
12 (c) The supervising certified applicator is responsible for the
13 following:
14 (1) Ensuring that the noncertified employee has received the
15 training required in this section.
16 (2) Keeping a record of the employee training required in this
17 section.
18 (3) Providing the supervised noncertified trained employee
19 with the means and instructions to:
20 (A) establish direct voice communication during the use or
21 distribution of fertilizer material; and
22 (B) immediately contact the Indiana department of
23 environmental management to report any fertilizer
24 material spill that may threaten waters of the state.
25 (4) Making work assignments to the supervised noncertified
26 trained employee.
27 (5) Knowing the status of the work assignments made to
28 supervised trained employee.
29 (d) A certified applicator may not supervise more than ten (10)
30 noncertified trained employees at any time.
31 Sec. 6.(a) An individual may become eligible to be a certified
32 applicator by passing the certification examination described in
33 subsection (b).
34 (b) The certification examination must be a written, closed book
35 examination developed by the state chemist. The minimum passing
36 score for the examination is seventy-five percent (75%) unless
37 another minimum passing score has been established by the state
38 chemist after consideration of the recommendations of the
39 standards committee described in subsection (c).
40 (c) The state chemist shall appoint a standards committee to
41 develop certification subject matter and standards for the certified
42 applicator certification examination. Members of the committee
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

35
1 include, at a minimum, individuals representing the following:
2 (1) The state chemist.
3 (2) The Purdue University cooperative extension service.
4 (3) The inorganic fertilizer industry.
5 (4) The organic fertilizer industry.
6 (d) A certified applicator's certification eligibility remains in
7 force from the date of completing the requirements in subsection
8 (a) through December 31 of the fourth year following the year
9 during which the requirements were met.
10 (e) The state chemist shall specify examination procedures that
11 must be followed by any individual taking an examination under
12 this section. Failure to comply with these procedures or any
13 unauthorized assistance provided by or received by an individual
14 during the examining period shall be cause for immediate
15 termination of the examining process for all involved individuals
16 and the involved individuals may not take the certified applicator
17 examination for five (5) years.
18 Sec. 7. (a) An individual may become eligible for certified
19 applicator certification renewal by completing one (1) of the
20 following:
21 (1) Passing the written examination for initial certification
22 under section 6 of this chapter.
23 (2) Accumulating at least three (3) fertilizer material
24 continuing certification hours (CCHs) before the expiration
25 of the individual's certification period.
26 (3) Attending at least three (3) fertilizer material private
27 applicator recertification programs (PARPs) before the
28 expiration of the individual's certification period.
29 (b) An individual may accumulate CCHs or PARPs only after
30 the individual is certified.
31 (c) An individual may accumulate a maximum of two (2)
32 fertilizer material CCH or PARP credits in any one (1) year of the
33 individual's five (5) year certification period.
34 (d) Credit for accumulating in excess of three (3) fertilizer
35 material CCH or PARP credits do not carry forward to the next
36 certification period.
37 (e) Eligibility for renewed certified applicator certification
38 remains in force through December 31 of the fifth year following
39 renewal unless the individual's certification is revoked or
40 suspended before that date.
41 Sec. 8. (a) The state chemist is responsible for evaluating all
42 instruction and training opportunities submitted for consideration
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

36
1 of approval for CCH and PARP credits.
2 (b) Training and instruction may be evaluated and approved for
3 both CCH and PARP credits.
4 (c) All requests for CCH or PARP approval by the state chemist
5 must be submitted as follows:
6 (1) At least twenty-one (21) days before the date that the
7 instruction or training event will occur.
8 (2) In a format determined by the state chemist.
9 (3) By an individual directly responsible for the CCH
10 instruction or training event.
11 (4) By the county extension educator with the Purdue
12 Cooperative Extension Service for the PARP instruction or
13 training.
14 (d) The state chemist shall use the following criteria to evaluate
15 and approve the instruction and training events for CCH and
16 PARP:
17 (1) The event must be open to all certified applicators.
18 (2) Except as provided in subdivision (3), any costs or
19 participation fees to cover expenses incurred by the training
20 providers must be the same for all certified applicators
21 attending.
22 (3) Professional educational organizations claiming Internal
23 Revenue Service 501(c) status and governmental
24 organizations may charge variable participation fees.
25 (4) The event may not be in-house training.
26 (5) The venue must be large enough to accommodate a
27 reasonable number of certified applicators from outside the
28 immediate organization facilitating the instruction or
29 training.
30 (6) The event must be open without fee or charge to the state
31 chemist for monitoring.
32 (7) The event must have an effective mechanism for the
33 person responsible for the training to verify participation of
34 each certified applicator from the start to the conclusion of
35 the CCH or PARP event.
36 (8) The event must include at least one (1) state chemist
37 approved regulatory topic.
38 (9) Subject matter and content must include at least one (1) of
39 the following:
40 (A) Fertilizer material storage.
41 (B) Fertilizer material chemistry.
42 (C) Fertilizer material equipment calibration and
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

37
1 maintenance.
2 (D) Fertilizer material use.
3 (E) Fertilizer material transportation.
4 (F) Fertilizer material application development and
5 implementation.
6 (G) Spill response procedures.
7 (H) Public and customer safety.
8 (I) Public and customer concerns.
9 (J) Applicator safety.
10 (K) Environmental safety.
11 (L) Environmental issues.
12 (M) Employee training.
13 (N) Associated state and federal laws or regulations
14 affecting fertilizer materials or fertilizer material
15 applicators.
16 (10) Subject matter and content may not include any of the
17 following:
18 (A) Product or service sales or promotions.
19 (B) Employee hiring or retention.
20 (C) General business practices.
21 Sec. 9. (a) A certified applicator who makes a false or fraudulent
22 report or in any way misrepresents the applicator's participation
23 in the certification renewal process is subject to the following:
24 (1) Revocation of all accumulated CCH and PARP credits to
25 date.
26 (2) The penalties allowed under IC 15-16-2-49.5.
27 (b) A person who makes a false or fraudulent report or in any
28 way misrepresents information that is part of the certification
29 renewal process is subject to the following:
30 (1) Revocation of authority and privilege to participate in any
31 future CCH or PARP events.
32 (2) The penalties allowed under IC 15-16-2-49.5.
33 Sec. 10. (a) A person applying for a fertilizer business license
34 must submit the following:
35 (1) An application to the state chemist on a form provided by
36 the state chemist.
37 (2) Except for a person that has paid a pesticide fee under
38 IC 15-16-5-48 for the current year, a fee of forty-five dollars
39 ($45) to the state chemist.
40 (b) An individual applying for a commercial applicator license
41 must do the following:
42 (1) Meet the certification standards described in section 6(a)
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

38
1 of this chapter.
2 (2) Submit an application to the state chemist on a form
