33 SECTION 50. IC 15-16-3.3 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
34 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
35 JULY 1, 2026]:
36 Chapter 3.3. Storage and Containment
37 Sec. 1. (a) Storage containers and appurtenances must be
38 constructed, installed, and maintained to prevent the discharge or
39 spill of fluid fertilizer.
40 (b) Storage containers and appurtenances must be constructed
41 of materials that are resistant to corrosion, puncture, or cracking.
42 (c) Materials used in the construction or repair of storage
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

45
1 containers and appurtenances may not be of a type that react
2 chemically or electrolytically with stored fluid fertilizer in a way
3 that may weaken the storage container or appurtenances or create
4 a risk of discharge or spill.
5 (d) Metals used for valves, fittings, and repairs on metal
6 containers must be compatible with the metals used in the
7 construction of the storage container so that the combination of
8 metals does not cause or increase corrosion that may weaken the
9 storage container or its appurtenances or create a risk of discharge
10 or spill.
11 (e) Storage containers and appurtenances must be designed to
12 handle all operating stresses, taking into account static head,
13 pressure buildup from pumps and compressors, and any other
14 mechanical stresses to which the storage containers and
15 appurtenances may be subject in the foreseeable course of
16 operations.
17 Sec. 2. A person may not store fluid fertilizer in an underground
18 or lined pit storage container. This prohibition does not apply to
19 the following:
20 (1) A watertight catch basin used for the temporary collection
21 of runoff or rinsate from transfer and loading areas.
22 (2) Storage in:
23 (A) a "316" or "317" stainless steel storage container; or
24 (B) a container approved by the state chemist, if:
25 (i) the storage container is enclosed within an approved
26 liner; and
27 (ii) an approved program of ground water monitoring to
28 detect leakage is established.
29 Sec. 3. (a) A storage container and other containers used at a
30 storage facility to hold liquid bulk fertilizer or fertilizer rinsate are
31 considered abandoned if the container has been out of service for
32 more than six (6) months because of a weakness or leak or has been
33 out of service for any reason for more than two (2) years.
34 (b) An abandoned underground container, including an
35 abandoned underground catch basin, must be thoroughly cleaned
36 and removed from the ground or thoroughly cleaned and filled
37 with an inert solid. All connections and vents must be disconnected
38 and sealed. A record of the catch basin size, location, and method
39 of closing must be maintained at the storage facility or as otherwise
40 provided for in this chapter.
41 (c) An abandoned aboveground container must be thoroughly
42 cleaned. All hatches on the containers must be left open, and all
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

46
1 valves or connections must be severed and left open.
2 (d) A secondary containment facility is not considered
3 abandoned because there have been no discharges into the
4 secondary containment facility.
5 Sec. 4. (a) Storage containers and appurtenances may not be
6 constructed of copper, brass, zinc, or copper base alloys.
7 (b) A storage container and appurtenances used for the storage
8 of fluid fertilizers containing phosphates or chlorides may not be
9 constructed of aluminum or aluminum alloys.
10 (c) A storage container and appurtenances used for the storage
11 of low (less than five (5)) pH fluid fertilizers may not be
12 constructed of ferrous materials other than "316" or "317"
13 stainless steel unless the materials are coated or treated with a
14 protective substance that is adequate to inhibit corrosion.
15 (d) A storage container and appurtenances used for the storage
16 of low pressure nitrogen solutions may not be constructed of mild
17 steel, fiberglass, polyolefins, or plastic. However, this prohibition
18 does not extend to nonpressure nitrogen solutions, commonly
19 referred to as twenty-eight percent (28%), thirty percent (30%), or
20 thirty-two percent (32%) nitrogen solutions. The prohibition
21 against the use of mild steel does not extend to aqua ammonia.
22 (e) A storage container and appurtenances used for the storage
23 of phosphoric acid may not be constructed of ferrous materials
24 other than "316" or "317" stainless steel unless the container is
25 lined with a suitable substance to prevent corrosion.
26 (f) A storage container and appurtenances used for the storage
27 of fluid fertilizers containing potassium chloride (muriate of
28 potash) may not be constructed of ferrous materials other than
29 stainless steel unless the container and appurtenances are:
30 (1) coated or treated with a protective substance that is
31 adequate to inhibit corrosion; or
32 (2) used for storage periods of not more than six (6) months
33 each and are completely emptied between storage periods,
34 cleaned, and inspected for leaks before being refilled for any
35 subsequent period.
36 Sec. 5. (a) A storage container must be anchored, as necessary,
37 to prevent flotation or instability that may occur as a result of
38 liquid accumulations within a secondary containment facility
39 constructed in accordance with this chapter.
40 (b) In addition to other means approved by the state chemist, a
41 container is assumed to be anchored if product is contained and
42 maintained within the storage container at least to the height of the
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

47
1 secondary containment walls.
2 Sec. 6. (a) A storage container and appurtenances must be
3 secured to provide reasonable protection from wildlife, vandalism,
4 and unauthorized access. The security must be provided by
5 fencing, lighting, or other means approved by the state chemist.
6 (b) Except for valves on empty containers or when a person
7 responsible for facility security is present at the facility:
8 (1) valves on storage containers; and
9 (2) valves on mobile fertilizer containers at a storage facility;
10 must be locked or secured.
11 Sec. 7. A storage container may not be filled beyond the capacity
12 for which the container is designed, taking into account the density
13 of the fluid being stored and thermal expansion during storage.
14 Sec. 8. Pipes and fittings must be adequately supported to
15 prevent sagging and possible breakage because of gravity and
16 other forces that may be encountered in the ordinary course of
17 operations. Except for an American National Standards Institute
18 (ANSI) Schedule 80 pipe or a pipe with a greater wall thickness or
19 hoses and piping made of stainless steel, all hoses and piping must
20 be located in a contained area or double sleeved. Underground
21 piping is permitted if the piping is:
22 (1) made of stainless steel;
23 (2) enclosed in secondary containment (a pipe within a pipe);
24 or
25 (3) hydrostatically tested annually.
26 Sec. 9. (a) Every storage container must be equipped with a
27 liquid level gauging device by which the level of fluid in the storage
28 container can be readily and safely determined.
29 (b) A liquid level gauging device is not required if the level of
30 fluid in a storage container can be readily and reliably measured
31 by other means approved by the state chemist.
32 (c) Liquid level gauging devices must be designed, installed, and
33 secured, in a safe manner, to protect against breakage or
34 vandalism that may result in a discharge or spill.
35 (d) External sight gauges are prohibited unless the gauge is
36 securely attached against the container wall and provided with a
37 manually operated shut off valve which is locked in the shut off
38 position at all times the level of fluid is not being measured.
39 Sec. 10. Except for the net weight of contents, every storage
40 container must be clearly and prominently labeled to identify the
41 container's fertilizer contents as provided in IC 15-16-2-32.
42 Sec. 11. Storage containers and appurtenances must be
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

48
1 maintained to minimize the risk of a discharge or spill.
2 Sec. 12. (a) This section does not apply to mobile containers used
3 to nurse field operations when at a field unloading site.
4 (b) An area used for the loading of fluid fertilizer into a storage
5 container or for unloading fluid fertilizer from a storage container
6 into a mobile container must be curbed and paved with reinforced
7 concrete or other suitable material that provides an impervious
8 surface and is approved by the state chemist. All activities at the
9 fluid fertilizer storage facility must be carried out within this area.
10 (c) The operational area containment must be constructed and
11 reinforced to support at least the foreseeable maximum gross load,
12 including the following:
13 (1) The product.
14 (2) Equipment that utilizes the operational area.
15 (3) The mobile container.
16 (4) The motor vehicle.
17 The curbed and paved area must have a minimum width of ten (10)
18 feet, a minimum length of twenty (20) feet, and a minimum
19 capacity of at least seven hundred fifty (750) gallons of discharged
20 fluids. Any fill or unloading point of the mobile container must be
21 positioned over the paved area during loading or unloading.
22 (d) With the exception of secondary containment areas lined
23 with synthetic or soil liners, and wherever sufficient capacity
24 required in section 13(c) of this chapter and this chapter are
25 complied with, the secondary containment area described in
26 sections 13 though 23 of this chapter may be designed for and
27 jointly used instead of a separate operational area containment.
28 (e) An operational area may not have a relief outlet or valve.
29 The base must slope to a collecting spot where liquid can be
30 discharged, by a manually activated pump, for use in the blending
31 process or for proper disposal in accordance with all applicable
32 regulations.
33 (f) All liquids must be promptly removed or recovered from the
34 operational area containment so that the capacity required in
35 subsection (c) is available at all times when operations are taking
36 place.
37 (g) Storage containers and appurtenances must be protected
38 against reasonably foreseeable risks of damage by vehicles
39 operating in the area.
40 (h) Alternative means, including portable operational area
41 containment systems meeting the capacity requirement, may be
42 permitted with prior approval by the state chemist.
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

49
1 (i) Operational area containment must be maintained, as
2 necessary, to assure compliance with this chapter.
3 Sec. 13. (a) Fluid fertilizer storage containers must be located
4 within secondary containment constructed with a base, perimeter
5 wall, and sloped floor. However, an exception for the sloped floor
6 requirement may be granted by the state chemist.
7 (b) The containment area must be separate from a secondary
8 containment area for other materials and used only for
9 containment of fluid fertilizer containers or other fertilizer related
10 equipment. This subsection does not prohibit the storage within the
11 diked area of anhydrous ammonia when stored in compliance with
12 rules adopted under IC 15-16-1. Adjoining secondary containment
13 areas may share common walls.
14 (c) Secondary containment not protected from rainfall must at
15 all times have a minimum capacity of one hundred percent (100%)
16 of the volume of the largest storage container within the contained
17 area plus the volume displaced by all the other tanks, equipment,
18 and appurtenances in the area up to the safe design level of the
19 containment structure plus a freeboard of six (6) inches.
20 (d) Secondary containment protected from rainfall is not
21 required to have the freeboard required in subsection (c) but must
22 comply with all other requirements of this chapter.
23 (e) A secondary containment constructed before July 6, 1991,
24 and having a capacity of a minimum of one hundred ten percent
25 (110%) of the volume of the largest storage container within the
26 contained area plus the volume displaced by all the other tanks in
27 the area up to the safe design level of the containment structure are
28 deemed to be in compliance with this chapter. Any such storage
29 facility that alters the secondary containment area or increases in
30 storage container volume must be brought into full compliance
31 within ninety (90) days of an alteration to the secondary
32 containment area or increase in the storage container volume.
33 (f) Tile drainage is not be permitted within or under secondary
34 containment.
35 (g) Alternative means of secondary containment, with prior
36 approval of the state chemist, may be permitted.
37 Sec. 14. (a) The walls of a secondary containment facility must
38 be:
39 (1) constructed of earth, steel, concrete (precasted modules or
40 poured), or solid masonry; and
41 (2) designed to withstand a full hydrostatic head of any
42 discharged liquid and weight load of material used in
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

50
1 construction.
2 (b) Cracks and seams must be sealed to prevent leakage.
3 (c) Walls constructed of earth or other permeable materials
4 must be lined as provided under sections 15 through 19 of this
5 chapter.
6 (d) Earthen walls must have a horizontal-to-vertical slope
7 consistent with good engineering practice. All interior slopes must
8 be protected with:
9 (1) flat road stone or a similar crushed stone material; or
10 (2) a minimum of six (6) inches of vegetative soils planted and
11 maintained with shallow rooted grasses.
12 (e) The top of earthen walls must be no less than two and
13 one-half (2.5) feet wide.
14 (f) Walls may not exceed six (6) feet in height above interior
15 grade unless provisions are made for:
16 (1) normal access and necessary emergency access to storage
17 containers, valves, and other equipment; and
18 (2) safe exit from secondary containment.
19 (g) Walls constructed of concrete or solid masonry must rest
20 upon:
21 (1) a floating base of concrete prepared to conform with
22 section 16 of this chapter; or
23 (2) suitable concrete footings that extend below the average
24 frost depth.
25 Joints between walls and base must be made watertight.
26 Sec. 15. The base of a secondary containment facility and any
27 earthen walls must be lined with:
28 (1) concrete;
29 (2) steel;
30 (3) a synthetic liner approved by the state chemist; or
31 (4) a clay soil liner.
32 Sec. 16. Concrete liners must be designed according to good
33 engineering practices to withstand any foreseeable loading
34 conditions, including a full hydrostatic head of discharged fluid
35 and static loads of storage containers, including appurtenances,
36 equipment, and contents. Cracks and seams must be sealed.
37 Sec. 17. Steel plates may be used for wall and base liners.
38 Installation plans must be approved by the state chemist, who shall
39 require that the plates are protected against corrosion and are
40 joined in a manner as to provide watertight joints.
41 Sec. 18. (a) Synthetic liners and installation plans must be
42 approved by the state chemist. The installation plan must address
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

51
1 proposed protection of the synthetic liner from mechanical
2 damage, vandalism, wildlife, and deterioration from exposure to
3 the sun according to the manufacturer's recommendations. A
4 synthetic liner may not be approved by the state chemist until the
5 manufacturer of the liner provides a written confirmation of
6 compatibility and estimate of the life of the liner.
7 (b) Synthetic liners must have a minimum thickness of thirty
8 (30) mils (eight-tenths (0.8) millimeters) and be chemically
9 compatible with the materials being stored within the containment
10 areas.
11 (c) Synthetic liners must be installed under the supervision of a
12 qualified representative of the manufacturer, and all field
13 constructed seams must be tested and repaired according to the
14 manufacturer's recommendations.
15 Sec. 19. Before a soil liner is installed, the surface soil must be
16 sealed, including the berm of an earthen dike, with a sealing agent
17 such as sodium bentonite, attapulgite, or a similar cohesive
18 material, including clay. The soil liner must be constructed in
