10 Sec. 10. Manure based fertilizers must be stored in a manner
11 that:
12 (1) minimizes the release of manure based fertilizer; and
13 (2) protects the waters of the state.
14 Sec. 11. (a) In addition to any applicable standards required
15 under sections 13 and 14 of this chapter, a storage structure must
16 be designed as follows:
17 (1) The bottom of the storage structure is at least two (2) feet
18 above bedrock.
19 (2) The bottom of the storage structure must be above the
20 seasonal high water table, unless lowered in accordance with
21 subsection (c).
22 (3) Test holes to obtain soil and water table information for
23 the design must be obtained as follows:
24 (A) The number of test holes must be sufficient to
25 adequately characterize the seasonal water table and soil
26 underneath the storage structure.
27 (B) Test holes must be:
28 (i) evenly distributed throughout the storage structure;
29 (ii) at least two (2) feet below the base of the storage
30 structure for concrete structures in karst and nonkarst
31 areas;
32 (iii) at least five (5) feet below the base of the storage
33 structure for earthen structures in nonkarst areas; and
34 (iv) placed to the shallower of either bedrock or ten (10)
35 feet below the lowest point of the proposed processed
36 manure storage structure;
37 in areas of karst terrain.
38 (C) Testing must be conducted by:
39 (i) a soil scientist registered under IC 25-31.5;
40 (ii) a professional geologist certified in Indiana under
41 IC 25-17.6; or
42 (iii) a professional engineer registered under IC 25-31.
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

60
1 (b) Plastic, fiberglass, and aboveground steel tanks must:
2 (1) have sufficient strength to withstand design loads;
3 (2) be watertight;
4 (3) be cleaned to remove any traces of previously stored
5 substances prior to addition of manure to the tank if the tank
6 is used to store any objectionable or hazardous substances;
7 (4) be installed to ensure the seasonal high water table is
8 maintained below the tank or the tank must be anchored to
9 prevent flotation; and
10 (5) have protected shut off valves for all inlet and outlet pipes.
11 (c) Any drainage system to lower the seasonal water table
12 around the base of a storage structure must be designed and
13 installed to:
14 (1) effectively collect and drain the ground water;
15 (2) be of adequate size, proper slopes, and proper distance
16 from the storage structure;
17 (3) if applicable, be provided with:
18 (A) sumps;
19 (B) pumps, including a backup pump; and
20 (C) electricity supply;
21 (4) if applicable, have a surface outlet that is at least fifty (50)
22 feet away from the storage structure and at least:
23 (A) fifty (50) feet from the property line in soils with a
24 permeability of one-half (1/2) inch per hour or less; or
25 (B) twenty (20) feet from the property line in soils with a
26 permeability greater than one-half (1/2) inch per hour;
27 (5) have a shut off valve or equivalent; and
28 (6) have an access point for sampling within fifty (50) feet of
29 the storage structure.
30 (d) A concrete storage structure must be constructed according
31 to the Indiana NRCS Construction Specification, Concrete
32 Construction, May 2015 and designed to either of the following
33 design standards:
34 (1) MWPS-36: Rectangular Concrete Manure Storages,
35 Second Edition, 2005.
36 (2) TR-9: Circular Concrete Manure Tanks, March 1998.
37 (e) A storage structure must not:
38 (1) have a discharge pipe or conveyance that would allow for
39 a release or discharge of processed manure or water
40 contaminated by processed manure; or
41 (2) be an underground steel storage tank.
42 Sec. 12. (a) The soil or foundation of an earthen storage
EH 1361—LS 7006/DI 150

61
1 structure must have a maximum specific discharge permeability of
2 one-sixteenth (1/16) in3/in2/day, 1.8x10-6cm3/cm2/sec. This
3 requirement may be satisfied by soil testing that shows a minimum
4 of three (3) feet of in situ soils that:
5 (1) meet the maximum specific discharge permeability
6 criteria;
7 (2) are over excavated a minimum of six (6) inches; and
8 (3) are recompacted to break up the existing macropore
9 structure.
10 (b) If there is not at least three (3) feet of in situ soils that meet
11 the maximum specific discharge criteria in subsection (a), a liner
12 must be used. Except for clay liners described in subsection (c),
13 liners used in a storage structure must meet the following design
